# Ask Before Changing

## Core Rule

When the user's request is ambiguous, under-specified, or could be interpreted in multiple ways, **STOP and ask clarifying questions** before writing any code. Never assume intent and make changes on your own.

## When to Stop and Ask

- The user describes desired behavior but not exact implementation details
- Multiple valid interpretations exist for the same request
- The change would affect foundational/shared state, data structures, or core game logic
- You are unsure which fields, properties, or systems should be involved
- The scope of the change is unclear (e.g. "swap equipment" — swap what exactly? just the cards? the slot properties too?)

## What NOT to Do

- ❌ Do NOT add extra changes beyond what the user explicitly asked for
- ❌ Do NOT "fix" or "improve" unrelated code while implementing a requested change
- ❌ Do NOT guess at the intended scope and modify foundational state (capacities, bonuses, buff states, etc.) unless the user explicitly says to
- ❌ Do NOT assume a broader scope just because it "seems logical"

## What to Do

- ✅ Re-state your understanding of the requirement and ask for confirmation before coding
- ✅ If you see multiple valid approaches, list them and ask which one the user wants
- ✅ Make the minimal change that matches the user's explicit request — nothing more
- ✅ If the user's description implies touching sensitive shared state, confirm first
